example.p:
Now, assume \sum_{i=1}^m c_i v_i = \vec{0}. We will show that each c_k = 0 using the linearity of the dot product.
\begin{split} 0 & = v_k \cdot \vec{0}\\ & = v_k \cdot \sum_{i=1}^m c_i v_i\\ & = \sum_{i=1}^m c_i (v_k \cdot v_i)\\ & = c_k (v_k \cdot v_k)\\ & = c_k \end{split}
Therefore we have derived the inequality.

statement.p:
 Consider the matrix equation \left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 1 & 1 & 0 \\
 1 & 1 & 1 \\
 0 & 1 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right)^n=\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 A_n & B_n & C_n \\
 D_n & E_n & F_n \\
 G_n & H_n & J_n \\
\end{array}
\right).  Identify formulae for A_n, B_n,\ldots , J_n.
